<Layout title="Selling a Brisbane Property With a Granny Flat or Secondary Dwelling | Daniel Gierach Property" description="Council approval status, disclosure obligations, CGT implications, and how to market dual-income potential honestly. What Brisbane sellers need to understand before listing a property with a secondary dwelling." draft={draft}>

<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do I need to disclose if my granny flat was built without council approval in Brisbane?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. Unapproved structures are a material fact in Queensland, and sellers are required to disclose them. Failing to disclose an unapproved granny flat can expose you to claims from the buyer after settlement. Before listing, confirm whether your secondary dwelling has development approval and building approval from Brisbane City Council. If it does not, get legal advice on how to handle disclosure correctly in the contract."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is the difference between a secondary dwelling and an auxiliary unit in Brisbane?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Brisbane City Council uses specific planning terminology. A secondary dwelling (commonly called a granny flat) is a self-contained dwelling on the same lot as a principal dwelling, typically up to 80 square metres. An auxiliary unit is a different planning classification with different rules around size and setbacks. The distinction affects development approvals, what can be built, and what must be disclosed when selling. Your council approval documents will state which classification applies to your structure."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How does a granny flat affect the CGT main residence exemption when I sell?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "If a secondary dwelling on your property has been rented to a tenant at any point, the CGT main residence exemption may be reduced proportionally. The ATO applies a partial exemption based on the floor area used for income-producing purposes and the period it was rented. If you have rented the granny flat, you should speak to your accountant before selling to understand your CGT position, as the calculation can be complex and the tax implications material."
      }
    }
  ]
}
