        onmouseover="this.style.color='#f5d07a'" onmouseout="this.style.color='rgba(240,236,228,0.35)'">
        ← All Articles
      </a>
      <span style="display:block;font-family:var(--font-sans);font-size:0.6rem;font-weight:800;letter-spacing:0.2em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#f5d07a;margin-bottom:1rem;">Sellers · 7 min read</span>
      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Selling a Brisbane Property With a Granny Flat or Secondary Dwelling
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Approval status, disclosure obligations, CGT complications, and how to market dual-living potential without making representations that will create legal problems later.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Properties with secondary dwellings attract motivated buyers across Brisbane's inner east, but listing them without understanding the approval and disclosure landscape creates genuine legal and financial risk for sellers. The questions buyers and their solicitors will ask about council approval status, rental income history, and whether the structure complies with current planning rules are not negotiable, and giving incomplete or incorrect answers can create post-settlement liability that is far more costly than any marketing advantage you might have gained.</p>

      <p>Getting this right before you list is not complicated, but it requires specific preparation that a standard pre-sale checklist does not cover.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Secondary dwelling vs auxiliary unit: the planning distinction matters</h2>
      <p>Brisbane City Council uses distinct planning classifications for different types of secondary structures. A secondary dwelling is generally a self-contained residential dwelling on the same lot as a principal dwelling, typically with its own living area, kitchen, and bathroom. The standard maximum floor area under Brisbane City Council's planning scheme is 80 square metres for a secondary dwelling, though this can vary depending on zone and lot size.</p>

      <p>An auxiliary unit is a separate planning category with different rules around size, setbacks, and the relationship to the principal dwelling. The specific classification of your structure affects what approvals were required, what can be marketed to buyers about the dwelling's legal use, and what a buyer can do with it after purchase.</p>

      <p>Your council approval documentation will state which classification applies. If you are not sure, search Brisbane City Council's online mapping tools for your property or contact a planning consultant before listing. Representing a structure as one category when it was approved (or built) as another can constitute a material misrepresentation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why council approval status is the first thing to confirm</h2>
      <p>Before doing anything else, confirm whether your secondary dwelling was built with both development approval and building approval from Brisbane City Council. Development approval addresses whether the structure is permitted under the planning scheme for your zone and lot. Building approval addresses whether the construction meets the relevant building codes.</p>

      <p>A structure can have development approval but not building approval (if construction was never certified), building approval but not development approval (if it was built as a non-habitable structure that was later converted), or neither. Each scenario has different disclosure and legal implications.</p>

      <p>An unapproved structure is a material fact in Queensland. You are legally required to disclose it. The failure to disclose an unapproved granny flat has been the basis for post-settlement claims in Queensland where buyers have discovered the structure cannot be legally rented or occupied. Before listing, confirm the approval status through council records or a building search, and get legal advice on how to address any issues correctly in your contract and disclosure documents.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How approval status affects your buyer pool and financing</h2>
      <p>An approved, compliant secondary dwelling significantly broadens your buyer pool. Investors can confidently market the rental income to lenders when seeking finance. Owner-occupiers planning to generate income from the dwelling can do so without regulatory risk. Banks and mortgage insurers increasingly require evidence of compliance for income-producing secondary dwellings when assessing borrowing capacity.</p>

      <p>An unapproved dwelling creates the opposite dynamic. Buyers who want to rent it cannot legally do so without first regularising the approval, which involves costs, time, and uncertainty. Some buyers will walk away rather than take on that complexity. Those who remain will typically factor the regularisation cost and risk into their offer, which means it comes directly off your price.</p>

      <p>If your secondary dwelling is unapproved, getting advice on whether retrospective approval is available before listing can be worth the time and expense. A legitimised structure at the time of sale is almost always worth more than an unapproved one.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">CGT and the main residence exemption</h2>
      <p>If you have rented your secondary dwelling, the CGT main residence exemption on your principal property may be affected. The ATO's position is that the main residence exemption applies to the entire property only if the property was used entirely as your home throughout your ownership. Where part of the property (including the secondary dwelling) was used to produce income, the exemption is reduced proportionally.</p>

      <p>The proportion is calculated based on the floor area of the income-producing part relative to the total floor area of the property, and the period during which it was used to produce income relative to your total ownership period. On a property where the granny flat represents 15 to 20 percent of total floor area and has been rented for several years, the CGT liability on sale can be material.</p>

      <p>If you have rented the secondary dwelling at any point during your ownership, speak to your accountant before listing. The tax position should be understood and factored into your net proceeds calculation before you commit to a sale price. It also affects whether the timing of your sale has any tax implications worth considering.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Marketing dual-income potential without creating false income expectations</h2>
      <p>Secondary dwellings are a legitimate marketing advantage when handled correctly. Buyers attracted by dual-income or dual-living potential are often motivated and financially strong. The challenge is marketing that potential without making representations about rental income that are either unverifiable or legally problematic.</p>

      <p>You should not state a specific rental income figure in marketing unless it is supported by a current, verifiable rental appraisal from a licensed property manager. Citing what you have been charging a family member, what the dwelling was rented for several years ago, or what you believe it could achieve are all representations that can create problems if the buyer relies on them and finds the figure inaccurate. Phrases like "potential rental income" without any dollar figure, or referencing an attached rental appraisal from a registered property manager, are safer approaches.</p>

      <p>The right buyer for your property understands that income potential involves tenancy market conditions, vacancy risk, and maintenance costs. Your marketing should attract that buyer profile rather than making income claims that will attract unsophisticated buyers who later feel misled.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Which buyers are most likely to value your property correctly</h2>
      <p>In Brisbane's inner east, properties with secondary dwellings attract three primary buyer profiles: multigenerational families seeking to accommodate parents or adult children, investors looking for dual-income yield, and owner-occupiers planning to use rental income to offset mortgage costs. Each has a different financial capacity and motivation.</p>

      <p>Multigenerational buyers are often equity-rich upgraders or downsizers and can be willing to pay a premium for a property that genuinely solves their family's living arrangement. Investor buyers are valuing the income more precisely and will be sensitive to the approval status, current rent, and what comparable rental properties are achieving. Owner-occupiers with income offset motivation are often first or second home buyers with strong income but limited equity, and their finance may be affected by how lenders treat the secondary dwelling income.</p>

      <p>A campaign that leads with the dual-living potential, confirms the approval status, and provides a rental appraisal from a licensed property manager gives each of these buyer types the information they need to form a confident view of value. That confidence is what produces competitive tension and strong results.</p>

